sentences: Phabullo Rodrigues da Silva (born November 1, 1993), known professionally as Pabllo Vittar (Portuguese pronunciation: [ˈpablu viˈtaɾ]), is a Brazilian drag queen and singer-songwriter.

Still in Minas Gerais, Phabullo took a university entrance exam by the Federal University of Uberlândia, where she was admitted to the full design course in 2013, but after some periods she dropped out of college due to her schedule of shows, which increased greatly due to the success of her music videos on the internet and her participation in the band of primetime television program Amor & Sexo.
Vittar appeared on TV for the first time in 2014, on a Brazilian talent singing show, performing "I Have Nothing" by Whitney Houston.

She became famous in the media in 2015 with the success of her music video "Open Bar", a Portuguese-language version of Major Lazer's song "Lean On" with original lyrics, produced by Bonde do Rolê and Omulu.

== Life and career == | === 2018: Não Para Não ===

sentences: On August 15, 2018, Pabllo Vittar released her second studio album Não Para Não – including the singles "Problema Seu", "Disk Me", "Seu Crime", "Buzina", and "Não Vou Deitar".
section: == Life and career == | === 2018: Não Para Não ===

sentences: On October 31, 2019, Pabllo Vittar released the 111 1 EP – including the singles "Parabéns" (with Brazilian rapper Psirico), "Amor de Que" and "Flash Pose" (with Charli XCX).

Following the success of the 111 1 EP, "Amor de Que" rose to success thanks to the 2020 Brazilian Carnival, with the song reaching over 50 million views in just a month; as of 2021, the song has over 138 million views.

Following the success of the 111 1 EP, "Amor de Que" rose to success thanks to the 2020 Brazilian Carnival, with the song reaching over 50 million views in just a month; as of 2021, the song has over 138 million views.
"Parabéns" was released as the second single and also enjoyed similar success, with over 127 million views on Youtube as of 2020.

On March 24, 2020, Vittar's third studio album 111 was released – including the singles "Clima Quente" (with Brazilian Jerry Smith), "Tímida" (with Thalía) and "Rajadão"; the songs from the EP were also included in the album.
In 2020, Vittar was featured in a campaign for Calvin Klein, as part of the designer's pride collection.

Soon after, she moved to Uberlândia with her mother, who had recently married.
She then began to go out for the night in Maranhão, to make friends, and to participate as one of a selection of singers in a house of shows.

She was now dressing feminine, but did not identify herself as a drag queen; the first time that she did drag was at age 17 in Uberlândia, to publicize a party of her friend by delivering pamphlets at the door of a nightclub.
Her first performance as a drag queen occurred at the Belgrano nightclub, of producers Ian Hayashi and Leocádio Rezende (whom Phabullo would later call her "parents").
In less than four months, the video reached one million views on YouTube.
In the same month she released "Todo Dia" as the second single of the album, which became notorious at Brazilian Carnival due to its lyrics.

The following year, she consecutively won again.

Vittar grew up listening to artists such as Aretha Franklin, Donna Summer, Whitney Houston, and Tina Turner, whom she imitated as a child before she even considered becoming a drag queen, as well as Gilberto Gil, Ney Matogrosso, Elis Regina, Alcione Nazareth, and Caetano Veloso.

She became interested in drag after watching the reality show RuPaul's Drag Race and cited RuPaul as an important inspiration: "All the drag artists in this world have to thank RuPaul for the visibility we have today."
Some participants of the show have also influenced Vittar, notably April Carrion and Naomi Smalls.
